  "short": {
    "headline": "What kills Indians? Partial answer from limited data",
    "dek": "Non-communicable diseases lead, maternal and neonatal deaths decline, but communicable diseases and injuries not covered.",
    "body": "Available WHO data offers a partial picture. In 2021, the age-standardized non-communicable disease (NCD) mortality rate was about 553 per 100,000 population (both sexes). The maternal mortality ratio fell from 658 per 100,000 live births in 1985 to 80 in 2023. Neonatal mortality stood at 31 per 1,000 live births in 2015 (latest available). These numbers show progress on maternal and child health and highlight NCDs as a major burden. But they leave out communicable diseases, injuries, and other causes—key gaps that prevent a full answer to 'what kills Indians'."
  },
  "article": {
    "title": "What the Data Says About Causes of Death in India",
    "standfirst": "Available WHO data on non-communicable disease mortality, maternal mortality, and neonatal mortality offers a partial but important view of what kills Indians. Gaps remain.",
    "bodyMarkdown": "The question 'What kills Indians?' is broad, and the available evidence covers only a few pieces of the puzzle. Data from the WHO Global Health Observatory provides three relevant indicators: age-standardized non-communicable disease (NCD) mortality rate, maternal mortality ratio, and neonatal mortality rate.\n\n**Non-communicable diseases** are a leading cause of death. In 2021, the age-standardized NCD mortality rate for both sexes was about 553 per 100,000 population (with an uncertainty interval of 425–765). This rate has been relatively stable in recent years, though estimates for 2020 and 2021 may be underestimated due to COVID-19 pandemic-related mortality classification issues.\n\n**Maternal mortality** has seen dramatic improvement. The maternal mortality ratio dropped from 658 per 100,000 live births in 1985 (with a wide range of 550–803) to 80 in 2023 (73–87). This represents a decline of about 88% over nearly four decades.\n\n**Neonatal mortality** remains a concern but also shows progress. The most recent data is from 2015, when the neonatal mortality rate was 31 per 1,000 live births (29–33) for the region covered by the DHS survey. Wealthier quintiles had lower rates (e.g., 14 per 1,000 for the top decile). However, no more recent national neonatal mortality figures are available in this dataset.\n\n**What is missing?** This evidence does not cover communicable diseases (e.g., tuberculosis, HIV, malaria), injuries, or other causes such as respiratory infections or cardiovascular diseases at a more granular level. The NCD indicator is a composite and does not break down into specific diseases. Furthermore, neonatal mortality data is only from 2015, and maternal mortality uncertainty intervals are wide. Without a comprehensive cause-of-death registry or broader data, a complete answer to 'what kills Indians' remains out of reach.\n\n**Why it matters:** Even this partial view is valuable. It highlights the shift from maternal and child health burdens to NCDs, and it shows where India has made progress (maternal mortality) and where data gaps need to be filled. Policymakers need fuller information to target health interventions effectively."
  },
